\begin_layout Standard
Thermohaline circulation (THC) is a part of the large-scale ocean circulation
 that is driven by global density gradients created by surface heat and
 freshwater fluxes.
 Stommel's box model (1961) is a qualitative description of the trends and
 equilibria in THC.
 This model couples the two fundamental drivers of TLC, temperature (
\emph on
thermo
\emph default
) and salt concentration (
\emph on
-haline
\emph default
), in a nonlinear fashion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename thermohaline.png
	width 70text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-dimensional 
\series bold
variables
\series default
 of Stommel's model are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

: temperature difference between the tropics (lower latitudes) and the North-Atl
antic (higher latitudes)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $y(t)$
\end_inset

: salinity (i..e, salt concentration) difference between the above two regions
 of the ocean
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-dimensional 
\series bold
parameters
\series default
 of the model are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{x}$
\end_inset

: relaxation time to a constant temperature difference between northern
 and southern latitudes in the absence of coupling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{y}$
\end_inset

: relaxation time to zero salinity difference between higher and lower latitudes
 in the absence of coupling.
 In practice, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{x}/\tau_{y}=\epsilon\ll1.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

: measure of freshwater flux through clouds moving from lower to higher
 latitudes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset Formula $\eta:$
\end_inset

 nonlinear coupling parameter between temperature and salinity evolution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this notation, Stommel's model can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\dot{x} & =-\frac{1}{\tau_{x}}(x-1)+\frac{1}{\tau_{y}}x\left[1+\eta^{2}(x-y)^{2}\right],\\
\dot{y} & =\frac{\mu}{\tau_{y}}-\frac{1}{\tau_{y}}y\left[1+\eta^{2}(x-y)^{2}\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that Stommel's model has a globally attracting slow manifold that governs
 the asymptotic behavior of THC.
 Find a leading order approximation to this manifold.
 (
\emph on
Hint
\emph default
: rescale time by letting 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\tau_{y}t.)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute the leading-order reduced flow on the slow manifold.
 Determine qualitatively the possible dynamical behaviors on the slow manifold
 as the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 are varied.
\end_layout

